author: @Shaniceyc
text:
I wonder how many hates I will get for this comment. First of all, Jisoo's vocal is stunning, unique song, creative choreography, one of most invested visual aesthetics of this era (as you would expect from BP's product) BUT I can't help but feel Jisoo's dance performance itself is like trainee level. It feels like Jisoo is too Diva, that nobody dares to criticise her work. What Jisoo needed is her blackpink pals to help her polish the dance. Jennie and Lisa have critical and natural sense of how to create angles, bends, expression, tempo etc to complement dancing and brings out aura.
Jisoo flower's MV at the current stage is blunt and disapproving. Especially the lining up spreading wings choreography (1:33 to 1:46). I wish the dance was as crafted as her outfits. Having said that, the awkwardness in the dance movement is what defines Jisoo and what she gives to us. She definitely seems to struggle in connecting with the dance rythm, and this imperfections itself should encourage anyone to pursue what you cherish instead of aspiring only for perfections. We all feel challenged with our careers, hopes and dreams but the struggle itself should not impede us to move forward and continue to create original works for the world to see like Jisoo.

text:
This song's lyrics express a romantic relationship that once experienced passion and beautiful moments but ultimately came to an end. The lyrics incorporate the imagery of spring, flowers, and farewells, depicting the beauty, brevity, and impermanence of love and life.

The lyrics mention that the protagonist used to be as innocent as A-B-C and Do-Re-Mi, but as the relationship changes, so does their gaze. This suggests that the romance was once beautiful, but over time, the attitudes and emotions of both parties have shifted.

The protagonist describes themselves as flying away like a blue butterfly, and everything that couldn't be captured is the other person's responsibility. This implies that after the breakup, the protagonist chooses to let go, blaming the irreparable relationship on the other party. Meanwhile, the lyrics mention that the once-blooming flowers and beautiful moments are now lies to the protagonist, meaning their love has become insincere.

The song mentions "lilac," symbolizing spring and pleasant memories. However, this beautiful relationship is ultimately cruelly destroyed. The protagonist questions whether they and the other person can both bear the end of this relationship, expressing the worries and unease after the breakup.

In the end, the lyrics mention that spring is coming, but their love is saying goodbye. This emphasizes again the impermanence of love and the changes in life. The protagonist finally decides to say goodbye to their past love, not looking back, and shedding the influence of the other person in the spring rain.

Through the portrayal of natural elements such as spring and flowers, the song demonstrates the beauty, brevity, and impermanence of love. At the same time, it also reflects the pain, release, and personal growth after a breakup.
